The following passage describes a runtime weight precision swap mechanism for on-device large language model inference. Read it carefully and continue the explanation. The key insight is that during a precision swap, weights of individual layers are replaced atomically while decoding continues, and the choice of how many layers to swap per decode step controls the latency profile observed by the user. Specifically, we can trade off between compute (number of swaps) vs. delay (total number steps). This allows us to both tailor our inference strategy for each workload as well as provide a simple way for users who don't understand all the knobs in their model
